                        <title>Letter from Charles N. Tenney to Adelaide E. Case, 1862 November
                        13</title>
                    </bibl>
                </head>

                <p>Charles apologizes to Adelaide for not more quickly responding to an earlier
                    letter from her, but explains that he has been ill and is only just recovering.
                    He promises to reply to her letter as soon as he can. He also comments on a
                    marriage and asks Adelaide to send his "compliments" to the happy pair. </p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">



            <div1 type="letter" n="1" id="d5">

                <head>Letter from Charles N. Tenney to Adelaide E. Case, <date value="1862-11-13"
                        >1862 November 13</date></head>
                <pb n="1" entity="DSSR_000000766_0659"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>"Office" &mdash;<date value="1862-11-13">Nov 13th 1862</date>.
                    </dateline>
                </opener>

                <p> I <orig reg="received">recieved</orig> your charming letter of the <orig reg="2nd"
                            >2<hi rend="super">d</hi></orig> just<lb/> as I was taking my letter of
                    the 9th to the office and<lb/> I thought I would wait and answer it. But, <name
                        type="recipient">Addie</name><lb/> mine, I had no idea of waiting <hi
                        rend="underline">six days</hi> ere attending<lb/> to that important and <hi
                        rend="underline">not unpleasant</hi> duty &mdash; but my<lb/> health was
                    in such a state &mdash; that I was unable to<lb/> attend to "office duties."
                    But lest I frighten you, I will<lb/> tell you all &mdash; just as it really
                    was &mdash; I had a slight<lb/> attack of Liver Complaint which troubled me
                    some, but<lb/> I am recovering from it now &mdash; <hi rend="underline"
                    >not</hi> in my <hi rend="underline">fancy</hi> &mdash; but really<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">getting well</hi> &mdash; I am somewhat thinner and
                    weaker than<lb/> I was, but that might have been expected &mdash; During
                    the<lb/> entire time, I have remained in the office &mdash; so you see I
                    have<lb/> not been "dangerous" by any means. I should<lb/> not have been so
                    explicit, but you are so fearful I half conceal<lb/> the real truth, but my
                        darling <hi rend="underline">rest assured I can conceal</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">nothing</hi> from you &mdash; which I know you so wish
                    to know,<lb/>
                </p>

                <p> I will not answer your letter now &mdash; for I cannot &mdash;<lb/> but
                    I will write an early reply. How kind and trustful<lb/> you are! I can only love
                    you more and more. Oh! how<lb/> I wish this War would end.<lb/>
                </p>

                <pb n="2" entity="DSSR_000000766_0660"/>

                <p>So <name type="person">Laurie</name> is no longer "Laurie" but <name type="person"
                        >"Mrs. Thompson</name>.<lb/> Please present my compliments and all the other
                    "nice<lb/> things," to the happy pair. Success and happiness<lb/> attend thee my
                    darling this Winter Do you like Farmington?<lb/>
                </p>
                <closer> Please write very soon to<lb/> Your own devoted and loving <signed>Charley
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
